<HEADLINE>
<P>
CIF BASKETBALL ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
HAWTHORNE LOSES TO LEUZINGER, 52-50, DROPS SHARE OF 1ST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STUART MATTHEWS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hawthorne High School's uneasy grip on first place in the Bay League was 
suspended for a few seconds on the back of the rim Wednesday night, along with 
a basketball that had been shot by Hawthorne's Anthony King. 
</P>
<P>
The ball dropped to the floor, giving Leuzinger High a 52-50 victory at home 
and toppling Hawthorne from its first-place tie with Beverly Hills. 
</P>
<P>
For Leuzinger (13-8 overall, 7-6 in league), the victory clinched third place 
and a berth in the Division 5-AA playoffs. It also avenged the season's first 
meeting between the teams, which Hawthorne (17-8, 10-3) won on a last-second 
shot by forward Reggie Bell. 
</P>
<P>
Neither team led by more than five points this time around. Hawthorne set up 
for the final shot with 17 seconds left, but Leuzinger's Troy Matthews broke up 
Waymond Powell's back-court pass. 
</P>
<P>
Hawthorne guard Tremayne Gauthier chased down the loose ball and hit Bell with 
a baseball pass. Bell charged to the hoop, but his layup sailed long. King got 
the rebound, but his short jumper didn't have enough on it as the buzzer 
sounded. 
</P>
<P>
"We didn't want to give up a three-pointer," Leuzinger Coach Phil Sherman said. 
"Against a team like Hawthorne, you've got to worry about everybody taking the 
last shot, especially Bell. But we've worked on our defense every day for about 
an hour and a half, and it paid off." 
</P>
<P>
The game began as a duel of fast breaks. Hawthorne ran to a 35-32 lead at the 
half. But Sherman switched to a stingy matchup zone in the second half, when 
his team held Hawthorne to only 15 points. 
</P>
<P>
Leuzinger was led by forward Ty Merriwether's nine points and 18 rebounds. 
Center Frank Willis also scored nine, and grabbed 10 rebounds and blocked six 
shots. 
</P>
<P>
Hawthorne's Gauthier led all scorers with 14 points. Powell added 13 and King 
had nine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
