<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: POMONA; 
</P>
<P>
COUNCIL AIDS HOTEL PLAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Pomona City Council has agreed to waive $243,235 in fees and spend $186,360 
on a water line to help the Shilo Inns chain build an all-suites hotel and 
restaurant at Temple Avenue and the Orange (57) Freeway. 
</P>
<P>
The new Shilo Suites Hotel, with 131 rooms, would be constructed within a block 
of the existing 161-room Shilo Inn. 
</P>
<P>
Shilo Inns owner Mark Hemstreet of Portland, Ore., told the council that 
construction could be completed within a year. 
</P>
<P>
Hemstreet said the existing inn has "lost a tremendous amount of business" 
because it cannot accommodate banquets for more than 75 to 90 people. The new 
hotel would have restaurant and banquet facilities seating 500. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement given preliminary approval by the council calls for the waiver of 
fees for a building permit, sewer connection and other charges. Hemstreet said 
the city's expenses would be offset within three years by revenue from the 8% 
tax on room occupancy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
