<P>
SEIZURE DRUG FOUND TO LOWER YOUTHS' IQS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A drug widely used to treat babies who have convulsions during high fevers can 
at least temporarily lower their IQs and should not be routinely used, 
researchers have concluded in a study published in the New England Journal of 
Medicine. The medicine, phenobarbital, is the drug of choice for infants with 
so-called febrile seizures. The researchers found a small but measurable 
decline in the IQs of youngsters who took the medicine for two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
