<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
SWEDISH ECONOMY 'FALLING APART' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
STOCKHOLM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Swedish Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson today said the economy is "falling 
apart" and his government will resign unless Parliament bans strikes and 
imposes a wage-price freeze for two years. 
</P>
<P>
The plan that Finance Minister Kjell-Olof Feldt outlined in Parliament would 
also put a two-year freeze on local taxes, rents and stock dividends. 
</P>
<P>
Collective bargaining is a pillar of the Swedish welfare system, which has 
eliminated poverty and guaranteed health care and education for everyone. The 
Swedish mix of socialism and capitalism became a model for the industrial 
welfare state. 
</P>
<P>
"What was known as the Swedish Model is, on the whole, gone, and this is just 
another sign," bank economist Nils Lundgren said on Swedish radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
