<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
GEORGIA GULF TO FIGHT TAKEOVER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Georgia Gulf Corp., moving ahead with a plan to avoid a hostile takeover bid by 
Texas investor Harold Simmons, filed today for permission to offer $200 million 
in notes to investors to back its recapitalization proposal. 
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta-based chemicals producer previously said its board of directors 
would make a decision on the $1.1-billion, or $45-a-share, unsolicited offer by 
Feb. 16. 
</P>
<P>
Until then, it advised shareholders not to tender their shares in the hope of 
gaining support for its previously announced recapitalization plan. 
</P>
<P>
Simmons' NL Industries Inc., a Houston-based specialty chemicals company, has a 
9.9% stake in Georgia Gulf and recently announced the $45-a-share offer. 
</P>
<P>
Georgia Gulf is hoping that a recapitalization will discourage Simmons' 
overtures. The company has valued the recapitalization plan at $55 a share, but 
Wall Street analysts value the plan at $45 to $50 a share. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Georgia Gulf set April 19 as the date for a shareholders 
meeting at which a vote will be taken on its plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
